<h1>Section 3</h1>
<h2>The List Element</h2>


<h3>Unordered list>/h3>
<ul>
  <li>Milk<li>
  <li>Eggs<li>
  <li>Flour<li>
</ul>
<p>gives bullet points before the text of each list item</p>

<h3>Ordered list</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Milk<li>
  <li>Eggs<li>
  <li>Flour<li>
</ol>
<p>Gives numbers before the text of each list item</p>

<p><ol></ol> and <ul></ul> need list items (<li></li>) in between then to work properly</p>

<h2>Nesting and Indentation</h2>

Inside a list item, I can embed another list

<ul>
  <li>Wake up and brush teeth</li>
  <li>Drink coffee<li>
  <li>Prepare for Gym
    <ul>
      <li>Wear gym shorts, shirt and shoes<li>
      <li>Drink a dose of Whey protein<li>
      <li>Use sunscreen</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>After gym, take a bath and go to work</li>
</ul>

<h2> Tag attributes</h2>

<tag attribute=value>content>/tag>

<p>Multiple attributes</p>

<p><tag attributeone=value attributetwo=value>content</tag></p>

There are global and specific attributes


<p>Anchor element: 
<a href=link>content</a>
</p>

<h2>Image elements</h2>
<p>The image element is composed of the tag <img> and the main component of this element is the attribute src, which gives the location of the image. It's also a self closing element</p>
<p><img src="url" /></p>
<p>Just like the lorem ipsum text, there's also lorem ipsum images avaiable at the website https://picsum.photos/200, which is useful to test images</p>
<p>The alt attribute provides an alternative text description of the image. It's important for the comprehension of blind people</p>
